# Wiki schema

This wiki follows Karpathy's LLM Wiki pattern
(https://gist.github.com/karpathy/442a6bf555914893e9891c11519de94f).

- **Topic**: {{TOPIC}}
- **Page language**: {{LANGUAGE}}

## Layers

- `raw/` — immutable source archive. Read, never write.
- `wiki/pages/` — LLM-authored pages. One file per page.
- `wiki/index.md` — catalog of everything in the wiki, organized by
  category, updated on every ingest.
- `wiki/log.md` — append-only chronological record of every operation.

## Operations

Three operations, per Karpathy:

- **ingest** — process a new source. Read it, discuss key takeaways,
  write a summary page, update the index, update relevant entity and
  concept pages, append a log entry. A single ingest may touch 10–15
  pages.
- **query** — answer a question against the wiki. Search the index,
  read relevant pages, synthesize a cited answer. Good answers should
  be filed back as new pages (typically under `synthesis`).
- **lint** — health-check the wiki. Look for contradictions between
  pages, stale claims, orphan pages, missing concept pages, missing
  cross-references, and data gaps worth filling with a web search.

## Page categories

Co-evolve these freely as your domain matures:

- `summary` — one page per ingested source
- `entity` — people, organizations, products, papers
- `concept` — ideas, techniques, frameworks
- `comparison` — side-by-side analyses
- `overview` — high-level framings across many pages
- `synthesis` — filed answers to queries that compound over time

## Page conventions

- Links use Obsidian-style `[[slug]]`. Slugs are lowercase, dashes
  between words, at least two characters.
- Frontmatter is free-form. Suggested fields: `type`, `created`,
  `updated`, `tags`, `sources`.

## Log format

Each entry starts with:

    ## [YYYY-MM-DD] <operation> | <title>

This makes the log greppable: `grep "^## \[" log.md | tail -5` shows
the last five entries. Keep operation strings consistent.

## Editing this file

This schema is yours. Edit it as your workflow evolves — add page
categories, tighten conventions, document domain-specific rules. The
llm-wiki-mcp server enforces atomic writes, etag-based conflict
detection, append-only log integrity, and path containment. Page shape
and schema are yours to evolve.
